I assume that by _semantic key_ you actually mean _symmetric key_, which is a &quot;shared&quot; **PRIVATE** key used to both encrypt &amp; decrypt data, as opposed to a private/public key pair used in asymmetric encryption, where one key is used to encrypt and the other to decrypt, or, well &quot;sign&quot; in this context (a bit more detailed explanation/example [here][1]).

With this in mind, if you take a look at the [javadoc of the JWKSet.toJsonObject() method][2], it reads:

[![toJsonObject() javadoc][3]][3]

Since this is a private key, you want to use `.toJsonObject(false)` to include all keys in the result, but other than that I don&#39;t believe there&#39;s anything to fix and your app should work normally. Furthermore, if you&#39;re building an auth server, please be aware that since the key is private it will also not be listed if you access the `jwks_uri`, eg: http://localhost:8080/oauth2/jwks

----

**Alternative way to create a `JWKSource` using a secret**

