AFAIR, you need to create a `handle` value by wrapping the Ballerina value. Then use that handle value and create a Java object. Here is a sample code snippet. 

There is no documented way to create a handle from a ballerina value. This looks like a gap in the interoperability support in Ballerina, and we will fix this in a future release. 

    import ballerina/jballerina.java;
    import ballerina/io;

    public function main() {
        json j = { &quot;name&quot;: &quot;John&quot;, &quot;age&quot;: 30 };

        // Step 1: Create a handle from the ballerina value
        handle handleResult = createHandle(j);

        // Step 2: Create a new Object instance using the handle
        Object jsonObject = new(handleResult);

        io:println(jsonObject);
    }

    function createHandle(any data) returns handle = @java:Method {
        name: &quot;createHandleValue&quot;,
        &#39;class: &quot;io.ballerina.runtime.api.creators.ValueCreator&quot;
    } external;

As per the code it uses Jackson databind to serialize the ballerina&#160;json object passed through java interop function. The serializer will serialize&#160;the whole object hierarchy&#160;of given ballerina json native object. So the it will try to serialize the type related objects in addition to json content too.&#160;

During the serialization, it will invoke all the Java getters for fields of the objects associated with the given json data. So the serializer tries to call &#39;getImmutableType&#39; method from the iterator type during the process since the ballerina string&#160;contains an iterator. Since the ballerina iterator can not be immutable it will throw an exception. 

Normal ballerina programs will never call the &#39;getImmutableType&#39; method during runtime for iterators. We do not actually need to serialize the types and other java objects associated with the json data, only the content.&#160;

One option would be to customize the serialization&#160;logic with jackson databind. Another option would be to use the ballerina/serdes module as below.

    import ballerina/io;
    import ballerina/serdes;

    type Student record {
        int id;
        string name;
        decimal fees;
    };
    
    public function main() returns error? {
